08680nam a22011535i 9783110357523DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019934409  a97831103575237 a10.1515/97831103575232doi  a(DE-B1597)425962  a(OCoLC)1149419529  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBM700b.M56 2012 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a296.422300aMinhagim :bCustom and Practice in Jewish Life /ced. by Hasia Diner, Jean Baumgarten, Naomi Feuchtwanger-Sarig, Simha Goldin, Joseph Isaac Lifshitz. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XII, 346 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRethinking Diaspora ;v300tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tTable of Contents -- tDetails of the Contributors -- tIntroduction -- tCustoms and Material Culture in Antiquity -- tThe Use of Amulets in the Jewish Community of Late Antiquity in the Land of Israel: A Glass Pendant Decorated with the Binding of Isaac, from the Hecht Collection -- tConservatism, Innovation and Custom in the Middle Ages -- tR. Eliezer b. Natan (the Ravan): Conservator or Innovator? -- tCompromise and Inclusivity in Establishing Minhag and Halakha: Contextualizing the Approach of R. Meir of Rothenburg -- tCustom in Ashkenaz in the Middle Ages -- tSefer Haminhagim (Venice, 1593) and Its Dissemination in the Ashkenazi World -- tThe Lobed Matzot: A Trialogue of Image, Text, and Custom -- tMemory Preservation and Custom in the Modern Era -- tTikkun ‘Shovavim’ in the Slonim Hasidut -- tThe Role of Custom in the Jurisprudence of the Mishna Berura -- tSephardic Customs as a Discourse Topic in the Ladinokomunita Internet Correspondence Circle -- tTo Plant Is to Remember: The B’nai B’rith Martyrs’ Forest and American Jewish Fundraising Customs for an ‘Evergreen’ Holocaust Memorial -- tDemons in the Yemenite Life Cycle: Folk Beliefs and Customs of Avoidance -- tThe Changing Role of Religious Custom in Reform Judaism -- t‘Everything Is according to the American Custom’: A New Custom for a New Country -- tIndex of Subjects -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Places0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aParallel to the Halakhic laws, the minhagim (customs) are dependent on local practices and the regional schools of sages and rabbis. The minhagim played a decisive role in the history of the Jewish communities and in the formation of traditions of religious rulings. They gave stability, continuity, and authority to the local institutions. The impact of Jewish custom on daily life cannot be overestimated. Evolving spontaneously as an ascending process, it presents undercurrents that emanate from the folk, gradually bringing about changes that eventually become part of the legislative code. It further reflects influences of social, cultural, and mythological tendencies and local historical elements of every-day life of the period. The aim of this volume is to examine the concept of minhag in the broadest sense of the word. Focusing on the relationship between various types of customs and their impact on every aspect of Jewish life, the volume studies the historical, anthropological, religious, and cultural development and function of rites and rituals in establishing the Jewish self-definition and the identity of the local communities that adhered to them. The volume’s articles cover the subject of custom from three perspectives: an analysis of the theoretical and legal definition of custom, an analysis of the social and historical aspects of custom, and an anecdotal study of several particular customs. Customs are a wonderful historical prism by which to examine fluctuations and changes in Jewish life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 20